               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18401214-name-145" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18401214-name-145" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401214-name-145" type="surname" value="HUNTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401214-name-145" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN HUNTER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of William Hunter, living in Charles-street, Somers Town. On the 30th of November, the prisoner came to my shop for a pair of worsted gloves—I showed him some which came to 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he tried on one, went to the door to call a person—he came back to the counter and put on the other, went to the door again to look for a person, and ran off down York-buildings—my daughter ran after him, calling "Stop thief"—he was taken and these gloves found.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18401214-name-146" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18401214-name-146" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401214-name-146" type="surname" value="HUNTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401214-name-146" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY HUNTER</persName>
                  </hi>, Jun. I saw the prisoner come into the shop—when he went out I followed him—I ran after him—there was no other man there—I ran till he was caught by my father first, the policeman took him from him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
